CMU art major discovers himself in his artwork    

MARIAH MOORE
The Pitt News

“I’m ready to talk about me and that’s
for sure,” said Jasdeep Jaitla as he sat
down in front of a computer showing a
screen saver of his bearded face.
Although Jaitla has never spoken forrnal-
ly about himself and his self-portraits, he
is deﬁnitely not a stranger to the art of
introspection. . ,

At 26, Jaitla, a senior art major at
Carnegie Mellon University, has done
many interpretations of himself since he
was a freshman, but that was not always
the case. When Jaitla arrived at the uni-
versity in 1995, he hadn’t really taken on
art before, let alone portraiture.

After receiving a self-portrait assign-
ment from CMU professor Herb Olds,
Jaitla said his ﬁrst self-portrait was so
“horrible” that Olds would not even dis-
cuss it in class. The drawing ——- the head
and shoulders of an eyeless ﬁgure with
only the distinctions of glasses, facial hair
and a turban ——- was “... almost car-
toony,” Jaitla said. He continued, “I used
Xerox copy paper, a number two pencil,
drew right in the middle of the page [and]
there was no contrast ...”

Jaitla admitted that when he was
younger, he did not know the language of

art, but as he talked he stood over scrolls -

of self-portraits in his hallway and it was
obvious that he has now not only_learned
it, but made it his own. '

Standing inside his modest apart-.
ment, the artist unrolled drawing after.
drawing — done with black charcoal on
huge white sketch sheets — and he
revealed many different angles of him-
self. One was of Jaitla turned to the side,
looking pensive with his hair draped over
his face. In another he screams at the
viewer with raised eyebrows and a
gnarled beard. Still others are much more
elaborate. One portrays Jaitla in the garb
of Jesus but wearing his turban as he
makes the sign of communion, and anoth-
er is of his reﬂection through a bottle of
water where his face and hands are gross-
ly distorted.

But these were the portraits he did
before he quit school for three years. As
his last self-portrait during that time, Jaitla
drew two ﬁgures, one over the other —-
one is screaming with his eyes pressed
shut while the other stares blankly, with
only vacant eye sockets.

J aitla returned to CMU last
September after some “self discovery,”
and his latest self-portraits have taken the
form of sculptures. Jaitla’s sculptures say
more than even his sketches do, and they

 

also hint at the conﬂict presentiin his last
sketch. A
Two of his sculptures are rife with

self-reﬂection. One is of a wooden choir

stage with clay pieces painted as ﬁgures,
representing the children in his third
grade class.

“I stood out,” Jaitla said of the. inci-
dent with which the work is concerned,
“not only did I look diﬂ’erent than every-
body with [my] dark skin, but I was wear-
ing a dark blue suit.” The piece is about
being different, but also “being part of a
whole,” Jaitla said. He did not want “to
say too muc ” about his piece.

“I like people to have their own inter-
pretations,” he said.

Another piece is also on the same
theme, but on a subconscious level. J aitla

-created a clay bust of himself sleeping on

a black box, inside of which is a relief of
his 9-year-old self — torn on a wall.
When J aitla was in third grade, his teacher

ridiculed his turban.

“The whole class then turned away
from me,” said Jaitla, who is Sheik.

He remarked, “a friend noticed the
tear [in the work] stopped at the turban.”

Standing with Jaitla among his self-
portraits — his sketches, his sculptures
and even photos of his art, “Who is this
person?” seemed appropriate to ask. What

would one think of J aitla? Perhaps that he
has much to unravel? Upon-meeting. him,

one sees a person with a slender build,-

golden brown skin and waist-long black
hair, but through his self-portraits, much
more can be learned.

Jaitla himself provided a reason for
doing self-portraits: “to ﬁnd out what
other people think we think of ourselves.”

{Jaitla will have hisnﬁrst art opening,
showing his self-portraits April 12 at the
Frame on CM U is‘ campus. _ .

